{"term":"1976","caseName":"United States v. County of Fresno","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1976/75-1262","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 08, 1976","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger6/oral_argument_audio/16311","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear arguments next in 75-1262, United States against City of Fresno.","start":0,"stop":43.745,"duration":43.75},{"text":"Mr. Shapiro I think you may precede when you are ready.","start":43.745,"stop":46.772,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the court.","start":46.772,"stop":50.655,"duration":3.88},{"text":"These cases are here on direct appeal by the United States and individual Forest Service Employees, from two decisions of the California Court of Appeals for the Fifth district.","start":50.655,"stop":63.721,"duration":13.07},{"text":"The sole question is whether a California Tax on possessory interests in improvements on tax-exempt land may constitutionally be applied to the occupancy of government owned housing by employees of the United States Forest Service.","start":63.721,"stop":83.611,"duration":19.89},{"text":"The amounts involved in these tax assessments are relatively small.","start":83.611,"stop":88.945,"duration":5.33},{"text":"The principal could be quite far reaching in view of the extensive amount of housing which is supplied by the United States to employees not only of the forest service but also of various branches of the Department of Interior and most importantly of the Military.","start":88.945,"stop":106.488,"duration":17.54}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me put this to the outset Mr. Shapiro.","start":106.488,"stop":110.785,"duration":4.3},{"text":"Suppose California and perhaps it does, but I am not aware of it, had a provision in an State Income Tax Law or a regulation that provided that whenever an employed person receives housing as part of his or her work, the reasonable value of that housing would be added to the net taxable income of the person portion of California income tax purposes.","start":110.785,"stop":143.938,"duration":33.15},{"text":"Would that be a different situation constitutionally from what we have here.","start":143.938,"stop":149.995,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it would Your Honor.","start":149.995,"stop":151.335,"duration":1.34},{"text":"In these cases the housing is not supplied free of charge.","start":151.335,"stop":156.197,"duration":4.86},{"text":"The employee occupies the housing although as a tenant at will.","start":156.197,"stop":164.812,"duration":8.62},{"text":"He pays compensation for it which is deducted from his salary.","start":164.812,"stop":168.231,"duration":3.42},{"text":"Now he does not pay in advance for the housing, he pays for the housing he has occupied each two week period.","start":168.231,"stop":174.497,"duration":6.27},{"text":"So this is not in any sense compensation to the employee.","start":174.497,"stop":180.31,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Shapiro could Congress declare this interest immune from taxation, could Congress do it, what do you think?","start":180.31,"stop":187.02,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"We believe that Congress could.","start":187.02,"stop":188.852,"duration":1.83},{"text":"It has not done so, because of the tax as we view it falls directly on in an incident of the employment of a federal employee, and hence a tax on the federal function itself.","start":188.852,"stop":203.65,"duration":14.8},{"text":"The constitution therefore bars the imposition of the tax under the doctrine of M'Culloch v. Maryland.","start":203.65,"stop":209.949,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think the constitution bars it to the extent that Congress could not permit California to tax it?","start":209.949,"stop":217.457,"duration":7.51}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe Congress can wave the immunity of M'Culloch v. Maryland, and I think it has, in some instances done so.","start":217.457,"stop":225.866,"duration":8.41},{"text":"For example, with respect to national banks, there is some limited taxation of national banks.","start":225.866,"stop":232.839,"duration":6.97},{"text":"On the other hand, that statute which permits national bank taxation is quite limited as this court held in the first agricultural credit a few terms back.","start":232.839,"stop":244.547,"duration":11.71}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"So it is not the same kind of prohibitions, as one would find in the First Amendment, for example.","start":244.547,"stop":251.091,"duration":6.54}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it is within the reach of Congress.","start":251.091,"stop":252.759,"duration":1.67},{"text":"But, Congress has given us some indication that it does not intend generally to wave the immunity of instrumentalities of the United States.","start":252.759,"stop":261.986,"duration":9.23},{"text":"In a somewhat analogous area, the Buck Act of 1942 subjects or rather provides that certain state sales and use taxes maybe imposed in exclusive federal enclaves.","start":261.986,"stop":284.042,"duration":22.06},{"text":"And the exclusivity of those federal enclaves is not bar to the imposition of that kind of a tax.","start":284.042,"stop":288.634,"duration":4.59},{"text":"However, the same statute in Section 107 says, “This statute does not consent to the imposition of state taxes on instrumentalities of the United States or the property of the United States”.","start":288.634,"stop":301.46,"duration":12.83},{"text":"And it is really that which is our position here, that here we are dealing with a tax on a federal function.","start":301.46,"stop":311.878,"duration":10.42}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Who the tax is levied on?","start":311.878,"stop":313.781,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"The tax your honor is levied on the possessory interest that Forest Service Employees have in government supplied housing for which they pay …","start":313.781,"stop":327.228,"duration":13.45}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"On their employees?","start":327.228,"stop":328.729,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"On the Government employees.","start":328.729,"stop":329.693,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And it is only for the part of the property that they use as personal property.","start":329.693,"stop":334.614,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the claim.","start":334.614,"stop":335.606,"duration":0.99},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":335.606,"stop":336.109,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But isn’t it true?","start":336.109,"stop":337.672,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that is what this states have contended.","start":337.672,"stop":341.569,"duration":3.9},{"text":"Now our answer to that, now that is what the counties have contended, our answer to that is the possessory interest of the employee on the residential side cannot be in fact separated from the governmental use of this property and this is reflected we think in the findings of the trial court which reviewed the assessments involved.","start":341.569,"stop":366.802,"duration":25.23},{"text":"The two trial courts here in Fresno County and in Tuolumne County, found that because of the inter-relationship between the residential and governmental aspects of the employees use and occupancy of this property, they had no possessory interest within the meaning of California law.","start":366.802,"stop":386.753,"duration":19.95},{"text":"Now the fact that the Court Of Appeals in this case, reversed that as a matter of California law but of course we are dealing with the impact on a federal interest of the state tax.","start":386.753,"stop":398.855,"duration":12.1},{"text":"And so the question of what that impact is, is not determined by the State Court’s decision.","start":398.855,"stop":406.18,"duration":7.32},{"text":"This is a question of federal law that has to be resolved.","start":406.18,"stop":408.862,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But we certainly take historical fact resolutions from the highest Court of the State, don't we, even in that situation?","start":408.862,"stop":415.686,"duration":6.82}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"This is not really a very historical determination.","start":415.686,"stop":418.747,"duration":3.06},{"text":"The real basis for the imposition of this tax was a California court decision in 1967, Caldwell & Klein against the camp (ph).","start":418.747,"stop":426.116,"duration":7.37}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not mean historical in the sense of time a memorial, but just determinations strictly of facts as opposed to law.","start":426.116,"stop":434.742,"duration":8.63}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, well, the basic facts are not disputed here.","start":434.742,"stop":438.332,"duration":3.59},{"text":"The conclusion from the facts which the Court Of Appeals drew is, namely, whether this possessory interest for purposes of determining impact of the tax on the federal function.","start":438.332,"stop":453.991,"duration":15.66}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the Government’s interest in this?","start":453.991,"stop":457.186,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government’s interest here is preventing the imposition of a tax on an incident of federal employment.","start":457.186,"stop":462.9,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"On its employees.","start":462.9,"stop":465.199,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when I say..","start":465.199,"stop":466.285,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government does not pay a nickel of this, right?","start":466.285,"stop":468.733,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"No Your Honor, but that has not been the test in this court’s decision.","start":468.733,"stop":472.029,"duration":3.3},{"text":"If in fact ..","start":472.029,"stop":472.771,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How are you going to know whether they would change the rules?","start":472.771,"stop":475.483,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think we are staying within them, Your Honor.","start":475.483,"stop":478.829,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not understand that if a house with four rooms and one of them is used as an office and the other three were used as a living room, a bathroom and a bedroom.","start":478.829,"stop":495.632,"duration":16.8},{"text":"Why they could not tax the three rooms and not tax the fourth room?","start":495.632,"stop":499.535,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the County of Fresno purported to do that.","start":499.535,"stop":505.119,"duration":5.58},{"text":"Now they purported in making their valuation here to exclude from the valuation, from the assessment, the office functions, if I may use that term, and the public areas surrounding the house.","start":505.119,"stop":518.981,"duration":13.86},{"text":"The County of Tuolumne did not make that kind of distinction.","start":518.981,"stop":522.544,"duration":3.56},{"text":"They did not exclude the office and public areas.","start":522.544,"stop":525.707,"duration":3.16},{"text":"They simply limited the assessment on the basis of the term of occupancy.","start":525.707,"stop":531.864,"duration":6.16},{"text":"But, I was about to tell Your Honor that the fact that the United States does not pay this tax out of its pocket is not the test -- this Court’s decision have clearly indicated that if …","start":531.864,"stop":543.697,"duration":11.83}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I did put that in my last question, my question was if the three rooms were used solely for personal reasons why that could not be taxed as personal reasons?","start":543.697,"stop":556.911,"duration":13.21}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I shall demonstrate when I go in to the facts Your Honor.","start":556.911,"stop":559.455,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"That is what I am waiting for?","start":559.455,"stop":560.247,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"The occupancy of the house is really not conveniently divisible into office and","start":560.247,"stop":567.675,"duration":7.43}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it is a 24 hour call?","start":567.675,"stop":569.872,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"It is partly a 24 hour call, it is partly…","start":569.872,"stop":571.939,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, aren’t you not on 24 hour call?","start":571.939,"stop":574.97,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not live in government housing, your Honor.","start":574.97,"stop":576.681,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but aren’t you not on 24 hour call?","start":576.681,"stop":579.163,"duration":2.48},{"text":"And you still pay taxes on your home don't you?","start":579.163,"stop":582.259,"duration":3.1},{"text":"And you do not complain, do you?","start":582.259,"stop":585.287,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in this Court, Your Honor.","start":585.287,"stop":593.683,"duration":8.4},{"text":"I think, I can illuminate my argument a little better by going into what facts the two trial courts found, and these basic facts have not been challenged.","start":593.683,"stop":604.387,"duration":10.7},{"text":"The courts really found that the employees do not occupy the housing as private citizens or use it for their own profit.","start":604.387,"stop":611.816,"duration":7.43},{"text":"They occupied as employees of the United States, and their right to occupy this housing is to serve the needs of the Forest Service.","start":611.816,"stop":623.113,"duration":11.3},{"text":"The Trial Courts found that they did not have..","start":623.113,"stop":625.541,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they have a choice whether or not to live in the house?","start":625.541,"stop":628.073,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Some employees do and some do not.","start":628.073,"stop":631.48,"duration":3.41},{"text":"Certain employees who are required to look after special equipment, who are on fire control duty or who serve the public during certain seasons must live in the government supplied house.","start":631.48,"stop":645.756,"duration":14.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there a distinction between those employees and those who could have a choice to live elsewhere?","start":645.756,"stop":650.21,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but there is a reason, there is a permissive category, however, the Forest Service requires that all of its housing be occupied in order to have people on the forest grounds, so that it will assign employees to that housing.","start":650.21,"stop":664.183,"duration":13.97},{"text":"Now employees of certain categories can refuse, but someone is going to be assigned to occupy that housing.","start":664.183,"stop":670.708,"duration":6.52}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"All of the employees pay something for the house.","start":670.708,"stop":672.352,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"All pay, all are required.","start":672.352,"stop":674.236,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Even those who are sent there have no choice or option to refuse.","start":674.236,"stop":678.077,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":678.077,"stop":678.677,"duration":0.6},{"text":"They all pay for the right to use the house.","start":678.677,"stop":680.295,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me understand this.","start":680.295,"stop":681.595,"duration":1.3},{"text":"They would at least ask to the Forest Service people, every occupant whether he was one who had the choice to live somewhere else or not, every occupant in effect is required to live in one of those.","start":681.595,"stop":693.734,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"In effect, he is required to live in and that brings us to the burdens of occupancy, which are common to all of the employees who live in the houses, whether the houses are required occupancy in the technical sense or permissive occupancy, in a sense they are all required to live in them.","start":693.734,"stop":709.705,"duration":15.97}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Shapiro, may I ask you a question about the computation of the tax.","start":709.705,"stop":714.086,"duration":4.38},{"text":"As I understand it, the rental actually paid maybe less than the real rental value of the premises.","start":714.086,"stop":719.003,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the formula for determining the rental actually paid is supposed to be on a comparable basis, comparable to the nearest established community.","start":719.003,"stop":729.788,"duration":10.78},{"text":"Then this is reduced by two factors.","start":729.788,"stop":733.543,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me.","start":733.543,"stop":733.995,"duration":0.45},{"text":"I do not need that.","start":733.995,"stop":734.705,"duration":0.71},{"text":"I am not so much interested in how you compute the rentals, or how you compute the tax.","start":734.705,"stop":738.753,"duration":4.05},{"text":"As I understand it, the tax is computed by capitalizing the economic rental value of the premises basically, is that right?","start":738.753,"stop":744.525,"duration":5.77}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"That is how the…","start":744.525,"stop":745.545,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"And if that is correct, am I also correct in believing that the tax would have been the same whether the rent was less, the same as or greater than the fair market value.","start":745.545,"stop":754.35,"duration":8.81}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, your Honor.","start":754.35,"stop":759.722,"duration":5.37},{"text":"I should point out that the County of Fresno made an express effort to reduce the tax for this office function, the County of Tuolumne did not.","start":759.722,"stop":770.207,"duration":10.49},{"text":"Going in to the nature of this occupancy, the first point is that the employees have no fixed right of occupancy or any lease or term of possession.","start":770.207,"stop":779.903,"duration":9.7},{"text":"Their possession can be terminated temporarily or permanently at any time the needs of the service require this --their right of privacy is sharply diminished.","start":779.903,"stop":793.47,"duration":13.57},{"text":"Forest Service personnel and Forest service business can enter the houses at any time, in fact it is common key system.","start":793.47,"stop":800.602,"duration":7.13},{"text":"The District Ranger, for example, can walk into a house to inspect it.","start":800.602,"stop":804.117,"duration":3.51},{"text":"The District Fire Control Officer can walk in to it, if it has a radio that is indented to be on 24 hour monitor service.","start":804.117,"stop":813.291,"duration":9.17},{"text":"The result is that the employee has neither a full right of privacy, as someone in private housing would have, his housing is solely for government purposes, the occupant has no right to a fix term.","start":813.291,"stop":831.685,"duration":18.39}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"From the City of Muskegon case, the person just had a permit rather than a lease didn’t they?","start":831.685,"stop":838.167,"duration":6.48},{"text":"This court said it was still taxed.","start":838.167,"stop":839.873,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Muskegon, I think illustrates the distinction we are making here.","start":839.873,"stop":843.633,"duration":3.76},{"text":"In Muskegon, someone had a right -- a private party had a right to use government property in the conduct of a commercial business.","start":843.633,"stop":854.135,"duration":10.5},{"text":"And in the Muskegon case, the court expressly reserved the question of what would happen if you are dealing with a servant or an agent of the government.","start":854.135,"stop":862.7,"duration":8.57},{"text":"Now, where the legal incident falls on a servant or agents of the government, the court has held that the tax is unconstitutional.","start":862.7,"stop":875.073,"duration":12.37},{"text":"That is illustrated in the Kern-Limerick, Inc. v. Scurlock.","start":875.073,"stop":879.196,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"You are not saying that is a general proposition are you.","start":879.196,"stop":882.207,"duration":3.01},{"text":"So broadly and to sweep the state income tax, is it not.","start":882.207,"stop":885.438,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no","start":885.438,"stop":885.855,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Just in this context.","start":885.855,"stop":886.939,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"In this context.","start":886.939,"stop":887.47,"duration":0.53},{"text":"I say that the legal incidents falls on the federal function, I am talking about the -- I mean a federal function not on someone who is a federal employee.","start":887.47,"stop":895.51,"duration":8.04},{"text":"For example, the courts long passed the taxability of..","start":895.51,"stop":899.591,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Shapiro, identify that federal function and indicate in what respect it is impelled or hindered by this tax.","start":899.591,"stop":908.598,"duration":9.01}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"The federal function, your Honor, here is the federal function for which occupancy of the housing is made available.","start":908.598,"stop":915.848,"duration":7.25},{"text":"The guardianship of the National Forest and the service to the public within the National Forest.","start":915.848,"stop":922.774,"duration":6.93}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is what way is that handicapped or interfered with by the tax?","start":922.774,"stop":927.419,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the tax can only have a relatively remote effect, in this case, on the carrying out of that function.","start":927.419,"stop":941.4,"duration":13.98},{"text":"We have argued below that it affected employee morale that it could lead to resistance to assignments because of the imposition of the tax, since one would have to accept this less convenient housing.","start":941.4,"stop":954.255,"duration":12.86}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you have any evidence or finding (Inaudible) of the operation of that?","start":954.255,"stop":956.706,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"No there is not, Your Honor.","start":956.706,"stop":958.028,"duration":1.32},{"text":"In our major contention, there is not such evidence on that.","start":958.028,"stop":961.934,"duration":3.91},{"text":"Our major contention does not turn on that.","start":961.934,"stop":964.576,"duration":2.64},{"text":"Our real argument on that aspect of the case is that if the tax, the legal incidence of the tax, is in fact on the federal function, then the court does not inquire as to whether there is any additional burden or interference.","start":964.576,"stop":980.143,"duration":15.57}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The federal function is sleeping and eating?","start":980.143,"stop":985.249,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Part of it indeed, is Your Honor.","start":985.249,"stop":987.266,"duration":2.02},{"text":"In order to keep this people on those premises for the period of time, it is necessary.","start":987.266,"stop":991.819,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And if they lived in a private home, they will pay all of these taxes.","start":991.819,"stop":996.119,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":996.119,"stop":997.175,"duration":1.06},{"text":"And they would have the greater right of privacy which is attempted on the occupation of private (Inaudible).","start":997.175,"stop":1001.601,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Shapiro, if they were not living on government owned land but were renting the equivalent apartment on private-owned land at exactly the same rent they would not pay the tax, wouldn’t they?","start":1001.601,"stop":1013.069,"duration":11.47}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"If they were renting?","start":1013.069,"stop":1014.213,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Paying the same rent for the same facilities, but that property were located outside the forest preserve then the man would not pay any tax at all?","start":1014.213,"stop":1022.838,"duration":8.63}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"The renter would not as this tax is drawn.","start":1022.838,"stop":1024.701,"duration":1.86},{"text":"I think, there would of course be a property tax on the land owner.","start":1024.701,"stop":1028.18,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But not on the occupant?","start":1028.18,"stop":1030.088,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Not on the tenant?","start":1030.088,"stop":1031.621,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"On the rented property, that is correct.","start":1031.621,"stop":1032.887,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Your tenant pays the tax and no other tenant pays who does not live on federal properties?","start":1032.887,"stop":1037.992,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"That is my understanding.","start":1037.992,"stop":1039.491,"duration":1.5},{"text":"Now, we have not claimed here that there is discrimination.","start":1039.491,"stop":1044.8,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But the District Court did, didn’t it?","start":1044.8,"stop":1046.926,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"The District Court found the discrimination.","start":1046.926,"stop":1048.907,"duration":1.98},{"text":"We have found that the discrimination we claimed aroused from the discrimination between the treatment of State Foresters And Federal Foresters.","start":1048.907,"stop":1057.853,"duration":8.95},{"text":"We found that that discrimination did not exist, so we withdrew our discrimination claim in this respect.","start":1057.853,"stop":1063.609,"duration":5.76},{"text":"Our brief expressly withdrew it.","start":1063.609,"stop":1065.363,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe I misunderstand the tax, but if I understand it correctly, if the forester lived off of government-owned property and had exactly the same premises, paid exactly the same rent, he would not pay this tax?","start":1065.363,"stop":1076.925,"duration":11.56},{"text":"The theory being that the landlord pays it.","start":1076.925,"stop":1079.621,"duration":2.7},{"text":"Here the landlord does not pay it because the landlord is United States Government?","start":1079.621,"stop":1083.923,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that is how the tax is drawn.","start":1083.923,"stop":1086.653,"duration":2.73},{"text":"Now before I …","start":1086.653,"stop":1088.5,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"A federal employee with the same earnings pays the tax that a non-federal employee does not pay, if he lives elsewhere.","start":1088.5,"stop":1097.376,"duration":8.88}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course what we focused on in this case was the imposition of the tax as it is drawn, a tax on a possessory interest in tax exempt land.","start":1097.376,"stop":1106.147,"duration":8.77},{"text":"That is the only kind of tax, we have been dealing with.","start":1106.147,"stop":1111.972,"duration":5.83},{"text":"We did not compare it to a tax on occupancy of non-tax exempt land.","start":1111.972,"stop":1115.689,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Shapiro, you said that tax was on the employees, in the question that I asked you.","start":1115.689,"stop":1122.684,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it is on the possessory interest of the employee and the housing he occupies.","start":1122.684,"stop":1128.788,"duration":6.1}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But it is on his interest in real estate.","start":1128.788,"stop":1131.255,"duration":2.47},{"text":"In a possessory interest in a piece of real estate --","start":1131.255,"stop":1133.046,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Possessory interest on the improvement.","start":1133.046,"stop":1134.617,"duration":1.57},{"text":"That is correct.","start":1134.617,"stop":1135.461,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Requirement (ph) for another piece of land.","start":1135.461,"stop":1139.774,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the tax lies on the possessory interest of the employee’s occupation of the tax exempt land.","start":1139.774,"stop":1147.129,"duration":7.36},{"text":"That is all we address are challenged to.","start":1147.129,"stop":1150.55,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Is any question raised here as to the computation of the amount of tax?","start":1150.55,"stop":1155.59,"duration":5.04}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the valuation is not an issue here, your Honor.","start":1155.59,"stop":1158.453,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"And I take it you are not asking that any case for all of the Michigan trilogy be overruled.","start":1158.453,"stop":1167.495,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"No your honor.","start":1167.495,"stop":1169.522,"duration":2.03},{"text":"We distinguish the Michigan trilogy on the ground that in those cases we were dealing with the use by private parties in commercial businesses of government property, either that had been leased to them or given to them under a permit.","start":1169.522,"stop":1184.296,"duration":14.77},{"text":"In this case, we are dealing with the imposition of a tax on a government employee for his possession and occupancy of government housing for a government purpose.","start":1184.296,"stop":1194.257,"duration":9.96},{"text":"In short, we view that as a tax on a servant of the government for an incident of his employment.","start":1194.257,"stop":1201.63,"duration":7.37},{"text":"We compare the case to Kern-Limerick, Inc. v. Scurlock, where a contractor using, acquiring government property was treated as an agent because those were the terms of his contract.","start":1201.63,"stop":1216.742,"duration":15.11},{"text":"He was acting as an agent of the government.","start":1216.742,"stop":1218.466,"duration":1.72},{"text":"The legal incidence of the tax fell on him and as a result, this court held in Kern-Limerick, Inc. v. Scurlock that the tax could not be sustained.","start":1218.466,"stop":1229.341,"duration":10.88},{"text":"Even though the economic burden in that case of the tax was the same as an earlier case, Alabama v. King & Boozer in which a contractor was similarly using government property but was not an agent of the United States.","start":1229.341,"stop":1246.672,"duration":17.33},{"text":"And that is why our central point here is that the employee’s occupation of the government owned housing here is factually inseparable from their duties as employees of the United States.","start":1246.672,"stop":1262.309,"duration":15.64}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well we are (Inaudible) is that if they are servants of the United States and taxed by them, taxed by the United States.","start":1262.309,"stop":1268.325,"duration":6.02}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1268.325,"stop":1269.601,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that your central point?","start":1269.601,"stop":1270.621,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"That is our central point.","start":1270.621,"stop":1272.021,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"When is the tax imposed?","start":1272.021,"stop":1274.277,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"This tax was first imposed in 1967.","start":1274.277,"stop":1278.164,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Was it imposed in advance?","start":1278.164,"stop":1281.181,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"In advance of?","start":1281.181,"stop":1282.895,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, was it imposed at the end of the year or during the year?","start":1282.895,"stop":1286.108,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this tax was imposed during the year.","start":1286.108,"stop":1288.859,"duration":2.75},{"text":"I think it is an annual tax and it is intended to be imposed.","start":1288.859,"stop":1291.53,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So a person with a day-to-day occupancy pays the tax for the entire year?","start":1291.53,"stop":1297.342,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"The tax is reduced by its actual occupancy, as my understanding, it is measured by its actual occupancy.","start":1297.342,"stop":1307.447,"duration":10.1}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"That is why the tax is such a small amount for each person.","start":1307.447,"stop":1310.088,"duration":2.64},{"text":"Isn’t it?","start":1310.088,"stop":1310.858,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in computing it, in fact, our findings of fact here show that these houses tend to be occupied three to four years at a time, and this was taken into account in the valuation process by the Counties.","start":1310.858,"stop":1324.481,"duration":13.62}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So, if some person is transferred in the middle of the year, will two different people be tax by the use of this property?","start":1324.481,"stop":1332.93,"duration":8.45}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"I assume that would be -- how it would be applied.","start":1332.93,"stop":1334.69,"duration":1.76},{"text":"Now we have been litigating the tax since it was -- it’s a relatively new innovation, this is the first case under it.","start":1334.69,"stop":1340.534,"duration":5.84},{"text":"It was imposed in 1967.","start":1340.534,"stop":1342.465,"duration":1.93},{"text":"This is the 1967 tax we are litigating.","start":1342.465,"stop":1345.275,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Shapiro, surely, I perhaps misunderstood your answer to my Brother Brennan’s question, but a tax on servants of the United States is not a tax on the United States is it?","start":1345.275,"stop":1357.52,"duration":12.24},{"text":"There are all sorts of taxes imposed upon government employees.","start":1357.52,"stop":1360.808,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I only meant servants of employees being taxed for an incident of their employment, not their compensation or not any other aspect of their lives, except so much of the taxes falls on their government functions, if as we contend here, the occupancy of the housing is inseparable from the government duties of the employees, and we think it is, then there is just no basis for trying to distinguish them constitutionally and therefore it is a tax on employees as an incident of their federal employment.","start":1360.808,"stop":1393.109,"duration":32.3},{"text":"That can not be done.","start":1393.109,"stop":1394.356,"duration":1.25},{"text":"If, for example, the county have not attempted to do this, imposed a possessory interest tax on government employees working in government offices saying, “Well, 5% of the time you are doing personal business on government time, we will tax you for that 5%.”","start":1394.356,"stop":1409.974,"duration":15.62},{"text":"We would argue that that is just inextricable from their government functions and hence is a tax on the government employee for an incident of his government employment.","start":1409.974,"stop":1417.948,"duration":7.97}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You made a de minimis argument which is what California makes it here that does so little of the use of these buildings as public and governmental use, so much of it is residential use, they are entitled to tax you?","start":1417.948,"stop":1431.432,"duration":13.48}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this goes to something that the Court Of Appeals attempted to do here.","start":1431.432,"stop":1437.695,"duration":6.26},{"text":"The Court Of Appeals rejected the conclusion of the Trial Court because they said that while government business was sometimes conducted from the unit, the business was completely incidental to the main use of the property.","start":1437.695,"stop":1449.185,"duration":11.49},{"text":"So it made the test of taxability turn on whether the government or the residential interest was dominant.","start":1449.185,"stop":1454.926,"duration":5.74},{"text":"Now we submit that this is not a proper standard for determining the constitutionality of state taxation of federal interest, that it leads to a great deal of confusion because you have to try and measure which is dominant when the employee is in the house 24 hours.","start":1454.926,"stop":1468.066,"duration":13.14}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But he did live there, he had a kitchen and a bathroom and a bedroom and the other rooms that my Brother Marshall described.","start":1468.066,"stop":1474.816,"duration":6.75},{"text":"There is his residence and that of his wife, because there was a preference given to married employees, isn’t that correct?","start":1474.816,"stop":1481.07,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, there is a residential interest without doubt, and we do not deny that.","start":1481.07,"stop":1485.149,"duration":4.08},{"text":"Our argument is that that residential interest exists solely for the purposes of the government.","start":1485.149,"stop":1491.512,"duration":6.36},{"text":"He is in the house to serve a government purpose.","start":1491.512,"stop":1493.753,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"He pays rent.","start":1493.753,"stop":1494.983,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"He pays rent to use the house.","start":1494.983,"stop":1499.574,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not like putting that in a watchtower or something like that.","start":1499.574,"stop":1502.147,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the watchtower would be a workplace and the county does not purport to tax the workplaces.","start":1502.147,"stop":1507.17,"duration":5.02},{"text":"But this also was a workplace, as the findings of the Trial Court, in fact the findings of the Court Of Appeals which agreed with that aspect of it, reflect","start":1507.17,"stop":1521.047,"duration":13.88}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose your answer would be the same to this hypothetical.","start":1521.047,"stop":1525.87,"duration":4.82},{"text":"The government sometimes increasingly, decreasingly so, allows employees who use automobiles to take the automobile home at night so that they can be on call.","start":1525.87,"stop":1536.525,"duration":10.66},{"text":"And, if the State of California tried to tax that use from, let us say, 6 o'clock onward, you would say they were taxing a federal instrumentality?","start":1536.525,"stop":1546.481,"duration":9.96}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, because I would assume that the availability of the automobile in the evening would have to be justified for government purpose.","start":1546.481,"stop":1554.889,"duration":8.41},{"text":"So really the heart of our contention is that the residential and the governmental functions of occupancy of this housing are inextricably interrelated.","start":1554.889,"stop":1565.012,"duration":10.12}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Shapiro, you could lose this case without depriving Congress of power to prevent this tax, you wanted to.","start":1565.012,"stop":1573.376,"duration":8.36}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Congress, I think can always speak directly to the questions in M'Culloch either way.","start":1573.376,"stop":1578.046,"duration":4.67},{"text":"They can wave the M'Culloch immunity or they could probably broaden their indications in the courts decision.","start":1578.046,"stop":1589.043,"duration":11}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"If we decided against you, you think that Congress the next day could say, well, the states may no longer tax this possessory interest of the employees?","start":1589.043,"stop":1597.886,"duration":8.84}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, they could, but to use this as a standard of constitutional adjudication would mean that the Congress would have to stay one step ahead of the state tax laws in every one of the jurisdictions.","start":1597.886,"stop":1607.577,"duration":9.69},{"text":"Keeping an eye out to see what new federal interest is subject to tax?","start":1607.577,"stop":1612.315,"duration":4.74},{"text":"Now, Congress instead has done the other way, as the Buck Act indicates, they have said, well, we will start with M'Culloch and Maryland which bars state taxation of federal instrumentalities and federal functions.","start":1612.315,"stop":1622.938,"duration":10.62},{"text":"And then we will decide when we want to wave it, that has been the approach and that is what the Buck Act strongly reflects.","start":1622.938,"stop":1628.999,"duration":6.06},{"text":"In fact, that was the basis of the courts decision in the Mississippi liquor case.","start":1628.999,"stop":1635.147,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think this case would govern the taxation of military personnel living on government bases?","start":1635.147,"stop":1643.515,"duration":8.37}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"We believe that it could, I hesitate to go into that because our record does not develop the facts.","start":1643.515,"stop":1649.818,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":1649.818,"stop":1650.514,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"But the reason we are here in large part is because of our concern that this kind of possessory interest tax will be extended to the military, which is the biggest body of government supplied housing.","start":1650.514,"stop":1660.966,"duration":10.45}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Shapiro, I think you may be covering up you five minute signal.","start":1660.966,"stop":1665.274,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"I would like to reserve the remainder of that time.","start":1665.274,"stop":1672.179,"duration":6.91}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Waterman?","start":1672.179,"stop":1675.179,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the court.","start":1675.179,"stop":1677.554,"duration":2.38},{"text":"My name is James B. Waterman, deputy County Council for the County of Fresno, California, and one of the appellees in this matter.","start":1677.554,"stop":1686.283,"duration":8.73},{"text":"I would like to take a few minutes to answer some of the questions that were asked at Mr. Shapiro, I guess, I am little more familiar with the taxing situation in California.","start":1686.283,"stop":1698.49,"duration":12.21},{"text":"There was a question as to whether or not an employee who resided in a private home or who rented a private home outside of the forest would pay tax.","start":1698.49,"stop":1708.725,"duration":10.23},{"text":"And the answer to that is you would pay tax but not directly.","start":1708.725,"stop":1713.372,"duration":4.65},{"text":"Anytime a person who owns a private property and leases it, they try to recover, of course, all that cost.","start":1713.372,"stop":1719.951,"duration":6.58},{"text":"The tax is assessed to the owner of the real property.","start":1719.951,"stop":1723.561,"duration":3.61},{"text":"And as a part of that income, the tax that the lessor would pay, would be included in the rental amount and I think that is the answer to that.","start":1723.561,"stop":1734.136,"duration":10.58}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The problem is, gives a tax on that government property.","start":1734.136,"stop":1737.224,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, because the government property itself is exempted, there is no questions.","start":1737.224,"stop":1741.562,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"You just want to attack the United States government property.","start":1741.562,"stop":1745.123,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":1745.123,"stop":1745.92,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought you said yes.","start":1745.92,"stop":1747.18,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, if I said that I misstated it.","start":1747.18,"stop":1750.196,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn’t that what you are after?","start":1750.196,"stop":1751.506,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, we want to equalize the obligation of people.","start":1751.506,"stop":1754.793,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The federal government had paid taxes on this property, you would not bother to (Inaudible).","start":1754.793,"stop":1760.408,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"As a matter of fact, the federal government..","start":1760.408,"stop":1761.352,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?","start":1761.352,"stop":1761.923,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, the federal government in effect; this was not brought out but there was a finding that and there is a regulation that the federal government where they do not have governmental housing sufficient to staff their people in the National Forest, they do have the option to go outside and rent private housing at the prevailing rates, and thereby put their employee into that house.","start":1761.923,"stop":1786.578,"duration":24.65},{"text":"The employee does not thereupon pay the same rate.","start":1786.578,"stop":1791.224,"duration":4.65},{"text":"He pays the rate that is determined by the rental survey and all of the things that Mr. Shapiro mentioned concerning accessibility and amenities in this sort of thing.","start":1791.224,"stop":1800.246,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But Mr. Waterman, if they take your example of one just off the reservation, one on the reservation, they both pay a $100 a month rent.","start":1800.246,"stop":1807.328,"duration":7.08},{"text":"So, you say the man who is living in the privately owned home in effect is paying tax because he reimburses the landlord for his tax.","start":1807.328,"stop":1814.444,"duration":7.12}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":1814.444,"stop":1815.266,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why isn’t the same true as to the man on the reservation?","start":1815.266,"stop":1818.115,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Because that’s taxation for possessory interest in California.","start":1818.115,"stop":1820.651,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the Government has given some taxation.","start":1820.651,"stop":1822.024,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1822.024,"stop":1823.479,"duration":1.46},{"text":"Because the government does not pay the tax.","start":1823.479,"stop":1824.538,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But both tenants have exactly the same economic burden.","start":1824.538,"stop":1827.38,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, and if this tax is upheld , he government employee will pay his fare share of tax whereby he does not now.","start":1827.38,"stop":1834.537,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"So he will pay like a $105 and the man who lives in private property will pay $100?","start":1834.537,"stop":1838.699,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, but it is build into the ..","start":1838.699,"stop":1841.576,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Simply because he lives on government property.","start":1841.576,"stop":1843.676,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1843.676,"stop":1847.276,"duration":3.6},{"text":"Now, I would like to address the M'Culloch v. Maryland argument in California possession of tax exempt property for your own personal beneficial use is a form of property and is so defined by the California statutes.","start":1847.276,"stop":1860.861,"duration":13.59},{"text":"M'Culloch v. Maryland prohibited only a state tax against an operation or function or an activity of the federal government.","start":1860.861,"stop":1869.372,"duration":8.51}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We will resume there first thing in the morning like 10 o'clock.","start":1869.372,"stop":1874.86,"duration":5.49}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 09, 1976","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger6/oral_argument_audio/16907","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Today we will resume arguments in United States v. County of Fresno.","start":0,"stop":7.012,"duration":7.01},{"text":"Mr. Waterman.","start":7.012,"stop":9.463,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the court.","start":9.463,"stop":13.807,"duration":4.34},{"text":"I wish to deal, this morning, with Title XVI of the United States Code Section 480, in which congress did express its intention that there should be a dual jurisdiction in the National Forest between the Federal Government and so far as the crimes against the United States are concerned, which were left to the United States.","start":13.807,"stop":37.88,"duration":24.07},{"text":"And reserving to the State wherein the National Forest is located its jurisdiction and it did not deprive the inhabitants thereof of their rights and privileges as citizens, or be absolved from their duties as citizens of the State.","start":37.88,"stop":54.212,"duration":16.33},{"text":"Now our contention is that one of those duties is the payment of the local ad valorem real property tax, and as has been expressed, since we are talking about property that is in the public domain and tax exempt.","start":54.212,"stop":68.1,"duration":13.89},{"text":"The only means by which such a tax can be paid is to through the possessory interest tax, in other words, the tax on the beneficial use and occupation of tax-exempt property.","start":68.1,"stop":79.237,"duration":11.14}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Can a state levy a sales tax on transactions within on national park, like Yellow Stone Park.","start":79.237,"stop":90.199,"duration":10.96}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe, I think it is Johnson v. Yosemite were that specifically was excluded, you are correct Mr. Chief Justice.","start":90.199,"stop":97.796,"duration":7.6},{"text":"However, the State of California does levy a sales-tax on retail sales in the National Forest areas.","start":97.796,"stop":106.862,"duration":9.07},{"text":"So, that has not been precluded.","start":106.862,"stop":110.238,"duration":3.38},{"text":"However, we are mainly talking about an increment of local property tax which benefits those inhabitants and I am speaking specifically now to the increment that goes to the local school district tax; that is based in California primarily on the local real property tax.","start":110.238,"stop":128.817,"duration":18.58},{"text":"Now, there was some testimony or a statement yesterday that some of these people have resided in these government homes in the National Forest for two or three years.","start":128.817,"stop":137.438,"duration":8.62},{"text":"There is evidence in this record, that in one case, an employee had been on the same single-family residence for fifteen years.","start":137.438,"stop":146.872,"duration":9.43},{"text":"Now during that period and of course this would be prior to 1968 when we started imposing this tax.","start":146.872,"stop":154.312,"duration":7.44},{"text":"In effect, he would have paid no increment, whatsoever, to the local school tax.","start":154.312,"stop":160.857,"duration":6.54},{"text":"If he had a six-year-old child when he moved into that home, that child would have gone through the local school district to the elementary schools, the high school, and two years of the community college if that were the case, being a hypothetical situation.","start":160.857,"stop":173.52,"duration":12.66}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Could the state not charge him tuition as a non-resident?","start":173.52,"stop":178.151,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, I don’t -- in a public.","start":178.151,"stop":180.262,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What could prevent that?","start":180.262,"stop":181.916,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"The Public School system of California provides for no-direct payment for non-residents.","start":181.916,"stop":185.962,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright I see.","start":185.962,"stop":187.033,"duration":1.07},{"text":"Could the state -- does it have legal power to say that someone living on a federal enclave?","start":187.033,"stop":195.861,"duration":8.83}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think not your Honor, I think -- obviously, they are citizens of the United States, they are citizens of the State, I think that they could not.","start":195.861,"stop":202.968,"duration":7.11},{"text":"I think it would be a denial of equal protection if they tried to impose that type of thing.","start":202.968,"stop":208.026,"duration":5.06},{"text":"Now it is different on a higher level of education, of course, Universities do charge an out-of-state.","start":208.026,"stop":212.452,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it you are not attempting to tax where the United States reserves exclusive jurisdiction.","start":212.452,"stop":218.888,"duration":6.44}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir; it is not allowed in California, by regulation.","start":218.888,"stop":223.287,"duration":4.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I have interrupted you.","start":223.287,"stop":227.408,"duration":4.12},{"text":"Does California attempt to apply this tax to anyone else who’s besides the United States government employees?","start":227.408,"stop":234.582,"duration":7.17},{"text":"What about -- are there other kinds of classes of people in this like ministers or...?","start":234.582,"stop":240.729,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, to my knowledge we do not apply it to ministers even though they might be residing in a mansion (ph) on tax-exempt property.","start":240.729,"stop":247.605,"duration":6.88},{"text":"However, for every tax-exempt special district such as Irrigation Districts, Core of Engineers, I might just give the court a couple instances as to how this case is going to effect other possessory --","start":247.605,"stop":261.841,"duration":14.24}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well what about other instances where property is tax-exempt besides that which is owned by the federal government directly?","start":261.841,"stop":269.71,"duration":7.87}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"County property, let me give you that for instance, if I may.","start":269.71,"stop":273.021,"duration":3.31},{"text":"We charge a possessory interest tax to our road supervisors in the County of Fresno who reside in county-owned residence.","start":273.021,"stop":281.563,"duration":8.54}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they pay a rent?","start":281.563,"stop":282.862,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, they pay rent and possessory interest tax.","start":282.862,"stop":286.848,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And income tax too?","start":286.848,"stop":288.703,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we do not have a county if they pay a state income tax.","start":288.703,"stop":290.676,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean the state income tax.","start":290.676,"stop":291.56,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, that is correct.","start":291.56,"stop":294.003,"duration":2.44},{"text":"Where there is a state forest, we do not have any in Fresno County, but they also, and this was one of the original intentions in this case was that there was discrimination because the State did not charge its own employees of possessory interest tax that is not true.","start":294.003,"stop":307.849,"duration":13.85},{"text":"And it is charged, they pay it on the same basis that we have been asking the federal employees to pay it.","start":307.849,"stop":315.223,"duration":7.37},{"text":"So, it is a non-discriminatory from that standpoint.","start":315.223,"stop":318.557,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this your answer to Justice White’s question about exclusive jurisdiction answer the government’s suggestion that next time you will be here trying to tax people in post housing on military bases?","start":318.557,"stop":332.878,"duration":14.32}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe it does Justice Brennan, after all, the California regulations -- we would have to change our regulations, and I think if we did that -- to me Congress has expressed the intention to be the exclusive taxing, if there is to be any tax in an inclusive military enclave.","start":332.878,"stop":353.278,"duration":20.4},{"text":"Now, I just don't foresee the State of California ever trying to tax any military in that situation.","start":353.278,"stop":363.351,"duration":10.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But counsel, how does the constitutional issue become any difference simply because California has not elected to try to impose the tax on exclusive federal property?","start":363.351,"stop":373.668,"duration":10.32},{"text":"If your theory is right, you would have the power to do so, I would think?","start":373.668,"stop":375.933,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think the question was asked yesterday whether Congress would have the power to exempt this type of property.","start":375.933,"stop":384.14,"duration":8.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but no -- I mean assume Congress has not done anything one way or the other.","start":384.14,"stop":388,"duration":3.86},{"text":"Would your theory not permit you to tax the occupancy of barracks on a military reservation?","start":388,"stop":395.308,"duration":7.31}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Not under the existing definition of possessory interest, your Honor and I --","start":395.308,"stop":398.235,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It would not under your existing regulations.","start":398.235,"stop":400.256,"duration":2.02},{"text":"But it would if you intend to -- but constitutionally you could amend the regulations and do so if you are right, but?","start":400.256,"stop":404.907,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"We would have to amend our definition of possessory interest also.","start":404.907,"stop":407.522,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But is there any reason -- any constitutional reason if you are correct, why you could not do so?","start":407.522,"stop":411.482,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I am sure we could.","start":411.482,"stop":413.826,"duration":2.34},{"text":"I am sure we would be right back in court if we did though your Honor.","start":413.826,"stop":419.034,"duration":5.21},{"text":"I think as far as in the case law, and we have foresighted the Michigan cases as authority for the imposition of this tax.","start":419.034,"stop":429.23,"duration":10.2},{"text":"We believe that Graves v. New York, which allowed the State income taxation of federal employees to be the closest and I could read the language from the -- there has been a claim here that somehow this tax burdens the federal government.","start":429.23,"stop":447.529,"duration":18.3},{"text":"One, we do not admit that these employees in their private housing which is furnished by the government for which they pay a rent.","start":447.529,"stop":455.101,"duration":7.57},{"text":"We do not believe that they are an instrumentality of the federal government for that purpose and therefore, the tax is permissible.","start":455.101,"stop":460.007,"duration":4.91},{"text":"However, the government who is also a party, plaintiff in this matter, alleged that there was a burden against the United States by reason of the imposition and collection of this tax.","start":460.007,"stop":470.051,"duration":10.04},{"text":"There was absolutely no evidence in the trials for these matters of any burden whatsoever.","start":470.051,"stop":475.467,"duration":5.42},{"text":"The government does not get the tax bill, the government is not assessed, the tax bill goes to the individual employee, and aside from 1967 to my -- it’s my understanding that these tax bills have been paid to the county without protest since that time.","start":475.467,"stop":490.889,"duration":15.42},{"text":"I could be on err on that --","start":490.889,"stop":492.326,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What if were not for the federal enclave the bill would go to the federal government, wouldn’t it?","start":492.326,"stop":498.547,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I do not think we have any right to pay, to bill the federal government for tax.","start":498.547,"stop":501.757,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I said if it were not for the federal enclave point.","start":501.757,"stop":506.482,"duration":4.73},{"text":"The bill then would go to the owner of the building, right?","start":506.482,"stop":511.616,"duration":5.13},{"text":"The landlord.","start":511.616,"stop":512.485,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No you Honor, we are taxing the person in possession in this situation and taxing their property.","start":512.485,"stop":517.585,"duration":5.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If the building was outside of the enclave and was owned by Mr. US, Mr. US would pay the tax?","start":517.585,"stop":526.677,"duration":9.09}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"We would not asses that property for it is owned by the United States.","start":526.677,"stop":529.96,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I said Mr. US, I did not say the United States.","start":529.96,"stop":531.358,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I am sorry, I thought you are referring to the United States as an individual.","start":531.358,"stop":533.265,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":533.265,"stop":534.517,"duration":1.25},{"text":"But if it was owned by the United States, then you would tax the tenant.","start":534.517,"stop":538.277,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct sir.","start":538.277,"stop":539.268,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But you really are shooting for the landlord.","start":539.268,"stop":543.356,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s in -- we do not divide the imposition or the tax in California other than in the tax-exempt property situation.","start":543.356,"stop":550.833,"duration":7.48},{"text":"The real property itself is security for the real property tax in California, and there is not a separate assessment to a private lessee from a private lessor, this is correct.","start":550.833,"stop":561.927,"duration":11.09},{"text":"I started to mention that we do have other federal land within the County of Fresno in which we are enclosing this possessory interest tax.","start":561.927,"stop":570.609,"duration":8.68},{"text":"We do have a rather substantial Veterans Hospital there, which has private -- well they are single-family residences for several doctors and the Administrator.","start":570.609,"stop":579.724,"duration":9.12},{"text":"They are very nice, high-valued homes.","start":579.724,"stop":582.564,"duration":2.84},{"text":"If we are concerned, and if this court does not uphold the district court of appeal, they will feel that they no longer have to pay a possessory interest tax and I think that would be the effect of such a decision.","start":582.564,"stop":595.448,"duration":12.88},{"text":"Core of Engineers also has a facility in Fresno County (Inaudible) flat were they built a rather nice den.","start":595.448,"stop":601.18,"duration":5.73},{"text":"They maintain -- maintenance people there in private, like private homes but on a federal property.","start":601.18,"stop":607.376,"duration":6.2},{"text":"We charge --","start":607.376,"stop":607.963,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Can Fresno County raise a considerable sum from this possessory tax?","start":607.963,"stop":613.548,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"In dollar wise, no your Honor, it does not.","start":613.548,"stop":615.952,"duration":2.4},{"text":"I cannot give you an absolute figure, but it is not substantial amount of money, I would have to admit that.","start":615.952,"stop":620.346,"duration":4.39},{"text":"However the --","start":620.346,"stop":621.044,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Approximately, how much?","start":621.044,"stop":623.058,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"At the time in 1968, I think the total amount at issue here is $178.00 for seventeen individual plaintiff owners, or residences, yes.","start":623.058,"stop":633.355,"duration":10.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Aggregate a $170.00.","start":633.355,"stop":634.332,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, but that was based upon a one-year tenancy at that time, and we are now -- because of the experience that we have had, we are now imposing a longer period to capitalize the income.","start":634.332,"stop":645.872,"duration":11.54},{"text":"So it is more, but I cannot give you an exact figure, sorry.","start":645.872,"stop":650.198,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And how about the possessory interest tax generally, well it just applies to this kind of housing, doesn’t it?","start":650.198,"stop":656.522,"duration":6.32},{"text":"Otherwise, it is a tax imposed on the landlord, correct?","start":656.522,"stop":659.062,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct your Honor.","start":659.062,"stop":660.046,"duration":0.98},{"text":"I do have some figures as to 1976 values in the Forest Land.","start":660.046,"stop":664.802,"duration":4.76},{"text":"Now, we tax other, you know, private business enterprises who lease from the federal government.","start":664.802,"stop":670.316,"duration":5.51},{"text":"The tax yield in dollars in 1975 was $89,622.00.","start":670.316,"stop":677.327,"duration":7.01},{"text":"We have a tax rate of $7.35 per $100 of assessed valuation in the Sierra National Forest and those are the figures that I am giving you now.","start":677.327,"stop":686.564,"duration":9.24},{"text":"Now, all of those, obviously, are not -- as a matter of fact a very small percentage of that tax yield would be from federal housing.","start":686.564,"stop":693.811,"duration":7.25},{"text":"We have a lot of family cabins that are located on 99 year leases, and that is were the bulk of that evaluation.","start":693.811,"stop":703.412,"duration":9.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think that the issue is the same -- the constitutional issue is the same with respect to your taxing commercial enterprises, who lease from the federal government as it is here?","start":703.412,"stop":715.749,"duration":12.34}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think it is different.","start":715.749,"stop":717.711,"duration":1.96},{"text":"I think -- and I think this is the contention that the United States is making.","start":717.711,"stop":722.204,"duration":4.49},{"text":"All the precedent up till now except for the Grave’s cases been where a private contractor, a corporation has been using government property for its own beneficial use and enjoyment.","start":722.204,"stop":733.533,"duration":11.33},{"text":"I do not think there is any --","start":733.533,"stop":734.871,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What is your possessory interest tax, interest tax on those enterprises?","start":734.871,"stop":738.98,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"We do.","start":738.98,"stop":739.383,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that raise a good deal of money for the county?","start":739.383,"stop":743.7,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, commercially for land and approved -- and these are commercial excises now; it’s $36,395.00 as of last year.","start":743.7,"stop":754.463,"duration":10.76}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If you think you could loose this case and still sustain or maintain your right to tax or a commercial enterprise.","start":754.463,"stop":760.143,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we do.","start":760.143,"stop":762.853,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Waterman, could I ask you two very brief questions?","start":762.853,"stop":765.604,"duration":2.75},{"text":"Is this tax unique to California, this possessory interest tax?","start":765.604,"stop":768.852,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I understand it, I think Michigan had a similar type of tax; it is probably not -- I think they call it a used tax of a sort there.","start":768.852,"stop":778.719,"duration":9.87},{"text":"I am not aware of any other states that have it your honor.","start":778.719,"stop":781.668,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The other question I had - does it -- does the imposition of the tax depend on the character of the possessory interest now there had not been a lease arrangement but rather and some kind of a license gesture, like you are going to a hotel room or something like that, would that be enough to impose it?","start":781.668,"stop":793.699,"duration":12.03}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"It has to be an exclusive possession under our definition.","start":793.699,"stop":796.906,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":796.906,"stop":797.419,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"And this is what the court found there was.","start":797.419,"stop":802.013,"duration":4.59}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well, Mr. Waterman.","start":802.013,"stop":803.512,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"James B. Waterman","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":803.512,"stop":806.588,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dietrich.","start":806.588,"stop":808.064,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the court.","start":808.064,"stop":810.109,"duration":2.05},{"text":"I am Stephen Dietrich Jr., county counsel with the County of Tuolomy, one of the defendants in this case.","start":810.109,"stop":815.953,"duration":5.84},{"text":"I am not sure that I should be here or Mr. Waterman, or Mr. Shupiro.","start":815.953,"stop":820.102,"duration":4.15},{"text":"I think that what the United States is fighting here is a different case and we do not have those facts.","start":820.102,"stop":827.172,"duration":7.07},{"text":"Our case, of course, before this court is a taxation of Forest Service Personnel.","start":827.172,"stop":831.964,"duration":4.79},{"text":"I think what the United States is fighting is the taxation of United States Military bases and Personnel.","start":831.964,"stop":840.152,"duration":8.19},{"text":"But we do not have those facts before this court.","start":840.152,"stop":844.41,"duration":4.26},{"text":"If the case would never arise in the County of Tuolomy, that is you could never get those facts before this court since we have absolutely no federal installations in the County of Tuolomy.","start":844.41,"stop":857.629,"duration":13.22},{"text":"The United States in its brief, talks about the twelve Forest Service Personnel and their families.","start":857.629,"stop":864.371,"duration":6.74},{"text":"In the county that they are residing, in the twelve residences in the County of Tuolomy, almost as if they were chattels.","start":864.371,"stop":870.059,"duration":5.69},{"text":"They are bound to the United States of America twenty-four hours a day, that is not so.","start":870.059,"stop":875.866,"duration":5.81},{"text":"They are living in these homes with their families, sending their children to our schools and albeit they may be on-call twenty-four hours a day, they have not sold their souls, as it were, to the United States.","start":875.866,"stop":890.27,"duration":14.4},{"text":"I cannot make a distinction between the twelve Forest Service Personnel we have here, and the many, many more Forest Service Personnel who work in the Stanislaus National Forest in our county, who reside off federal premises.","start":890.27,"stop":907.339,"duration":17.07},{"text":"They either purchase homes, and many do, or they rent property.","start":907.339,"stop":911.324,"duration":3.98},{"text":"When they purchase their home, they must pay a property tax as a homeowner, when they rent they are indirectly paying property tax unless they have a landlord who does not want to recoup his payment of taxes.","start":911.324,"stop":925.059,"duration":13.74},{"text":"And if this particular individuals living in a forest service housing are allowed not to pay a tax or a rule the tax is unconstitutional, they are really getting a better deal than their counterparts living out on the economy as it were.","start":925.059,"stop":939.299,"duration":14.24}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dietrich?","start":939.299,"stop":940.298,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":940.298,"stop":940.968,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What services other than the public schools are provided to these residents by the county?","start":940.968,"stop":947.759,"duration":6.79}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They use our county roads, they use our county mental health services, it’s only if they wish, and I am not saying they all do.","start":947.759,"stop":954.554,"duration":6.79},{"text":"The schools and all the other services that the county provides with the county hospital; if they should qualify, they may take part in our welfare system.","start":954.554,"stop":966.963,"duration":12.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they have any fire protection or police protection from the County?","start":966.963,"stop":970.897,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, the sheriff’s department provides in the un-incorporated area in our County and the County is -- in our County at least anyway we are just starting to get into a County-wide fire protection program.","start":970.897,"stop":981.34,"duration":10.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the County sheriff have any jurisdiction within the fire --","start":981.34,"stop":984.585,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":984.585,"stop":987.924,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How many people in the Ranger service are on welfare?","start":987.924,"stop":993.286,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven’t the slightest idea your Honor.","start":993.286,"stop":994.39,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why didn’t you say so?","start":994.39,"stop":996.588,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well they would be a -- they may qualify.","start":996.588,"stop":998.555,"duration":1.97},{"text":"The rules are always changing, I do not think any of them do yet, but the rules change so fast my Welfare Director cannot keep-up with them.","start":998.555,"stop":1005.815,"duration":7.26},{"text":"Perhaps a particular factual situation might allow them to qualify.","start":1005.815,"stop":1010.279,"duration":4.46},{"text":"I do not think there are any on it now.","start":1010.279,"stop":1011.975,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would you mind if that doesn’t persuade me anyway.","start":1011.975,"stop":1014.055,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s -- yes your Honor.","start":1014.055,"stop":1015.68,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dietrich, I did not quite follow you.","start":1015.68,"stop":1017.256,"duration":1.58},{"text":"Just before we started questioning, you said that those who live on the enclave would get a better deal than those who lived off.","start":1017.256,"stop":1024.744,"duration":7.49},{"text":"I though it would be just the reverse.","start":1024.744,"stop":1027.723,"duration":2.98},{"text":"Because if they both pay the fair rental value of the property, the one on the -- the forester would also pay the tax the other one would not?","start":1027.723,"stop":1035.329,"duration":7.61}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But they are both would end-up paying a tax and I think it was testimony in our case to the County of Fresno that the federal government really does not take into consideration the taxes -- that is right, I recall that, take into consideration taxes in their formula.","start":1035.329,"stop":1051.323,"duration":15.99},{"text":"So actually, the federal government I suppose is turning a profit.","start":1051.323,"stop":1053.782,"duration":2.46},{"text":"It might, dollar wise, balance out in your case I think.","start":1053.782,"stop":1056.573,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":1056.573,"stop":1061.558,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But the end result is they would not support our services and the way we look at it is that these people are making a private beneficial use of this property.","start":1061.558,"stop":1069.583,"duration":8.03},{"text":"They are living on it as a home.","start":1069.583,"stop":1071.647,"duration":2.06},{"text":"They are not a $100,000 houses, but the testimony in the case was that people living in the homes found them quite adequate for themselves and for their families, and they did not think they were getting that bad of a deal.","start":1071.647,"stop":1088.387,"duration":16.74},{"text":"We believe that these people should help pay for all those services excluding welfare, that they may be using just like I use, and just like all the rest of the Forest Service Personnel and the staffs of our National Forest use.","start":1088.387,"stop":1104.596,"duration":16.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you agree with proposition that what you are really doing, is since you cannot collect the money from the owner, the landlord, you collect it from the tenant?","start":1104.596,"stop":1118.096,"duration":13.5}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is what in effect we are doing, yes.","start":1118.096,"stop":1119.805,"duration":1.71},{"text":"We could not collect it from the United States.","start":1119.805,"stop":1123.104,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And so you are collecting it from the tenant.","start":1123.104,"stop":1125.517,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it comes from the individual.","start":1125.517,"stop":1127.085,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"From the tenant.","start":1127.085,"stop":1128.327,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"From the tenant.","start":1128.327,"stop":1129.211,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And it is really aimed at the landlord.","start":1129.211,"stop":1131.47,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it is for the individual --","start":1131.47,"stop":1132.507,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Now what is the other one, what is the (Inaudible) long tax?","start":1132.507,"stop":1137.232,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It is on the property itself.","start":1137.232,"stop":1139.043,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that aimed at the tenant?","start":1139.043,"stop":1141.51,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Let us say, if the landlord lives there it is aimed at him, it’s the owner of the property.","start":1141.51,"stop":1145.107,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right, but you really want to collect that long tax on government property.","start":1145.107,"stop":1151.49,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Because of their private beneficial use of the property.","start":1151.49,"stop":1153.968,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right, but you want it at the long property owned by the federal government.","start":1153.968,"stop":1159.32,"duration":5.35}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1159.32,"stop":1161.242,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dietrich, you identified the services that this people get.","start":1161.242,"stop":1164.951,"duration":3.71},{"text":"Are there other taxes that the County imposes that these people pay?","start":1164.951,"stop":1169.023,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we have quite a bag of ways to gather taxes. Sales tax, property tax, or possessory interest tax, hotel/motel tax, we get an awful lot of subvention funds from both the federal government and from the State of California.","start":1169.023,"stop":1185.955,"duration":16.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Gasoline tax.","start":1185.955,"stop":1187.36,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Gasoline tax.","start":1187.36,"stop":1188.036,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Cigarette tax.","start":1188.036,"stop":1189.553,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Cigarette tax.","start":1189.553,"stop":1190.214,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Liquor tax, you name it.","start":1190.214,"stop":1192.598,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If it those we try to tax them.","start":1192.598,"stop":1199.785,"duration":7.19},{"text":"I have nothing further.","start":1199.785,"stop":1200.039,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I was one question though, in describing property, just the ordinary property outside the forest, the Federal Forest are, you do not worry about putting a use tax on him because you have collected real estate tax on the house.","start":1200.039,"stop":1213.807,"duration":13.77}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct your Honor.","start":1213.807,"stop":1214.897,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So that in that sense, Justice Marshall’s suggestion would appear to be that this is a substitute for that tax.","start":1214.897,"stop":1222.801,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, yes.","start":1222.801,"stop":1226.805,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Or it could in other ways be an indirect (Inaudible).","start":1226.805,"stop":1232.277,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen Dietrich, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We think we can do this.","start":1232.277,"stop":1236.003,"duration":3.73},{"text":"Thank you, your Honor.","start":1236.003,"stop":1238.516,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Dietrich.","start":1238.516,"stop":1241.751,"duration":3.23},{"text":"You have about three minutes left Mr. Shupiro.","start":1241.751,"stop":1244.412,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you your Honor.","start":1244.412,"stop":1245.313,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Shupiro, if you have -- would you suggest what you think about the exclusive enclave?","start":1245.313,"stop":1253.431,"duration":8.12}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, your Honor.","start":1253.431,"stop":1255.032,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I gather, we have been told that at least Fresno’s regulations do not apply to this tax.","start":1255.032,"stop":1261.665,"duration":6.63},{"text":"Let us say the military, living in housing on the exclusive enclave, but he does say that constitutionally he thinks it can be done.","start":1261.665,"stop":1271.583,"duration":9.92}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, your Honor.","start":1271.583,"stop":1275.077,"duration":3.49},{"text":"We are informed by the Department of the Navy that Humboldt County in California is attempting to tax Navy housing, so that the potential for the imposition of this tax on the military exists now.","start":1275.077,"stop":1288.096,"duration":13.02},{"text":"With respect to this specific case, I should point out that 16 U. S. C. 480 provides that state civil and criminal jurisdiction continued to apply in National Forest areas, so that we are not dealing with an exclusive federal enclave when we talk about National Forest.","start":1288.096,"stop":1307.163,"duration":19.07},{"text":"However, 16 U. S. C. 480 is not a waiver of this immunity of the United States, its instrumentalities, or its officers in connection with their duties from the imposition of state taxes.","start":1307.163,"stop":1319.109,"duration":11.95},{"text":"Now there is second major point I would like to make.","start":1319.109,"stop":1321.62,"duration":2.51},{"text":"The counties claim they are simply seeking to make up revenues lost, because National Forests are not taxable since it is United States property.","start":1321.62,"stop":1331.956,"duration":10.34},{"text":"16 U.S. Code Section 500 provides that the counties shall receive 25% of the receipts from the National Forests located in their jurisdiction to be applied for roads and schools.","start":1331.956,"stop":1346.051,"duration":14.1},{"text":"So Congress has enacted a kind of in lieu tax, because the National Forests are not themselves directly taxable.","start":1346.051,"stop":1354.801,"duration":8.75},{"text":"Now there is one other point, because the tax is on a federal function in our view, there is no requirement that a burden or interference of any other kind be shown and that the tax has been imposed.","start":1354.801,"stop":1369.707,"duration":14.91},{"text":"This court has held that National Banks are not taxable by States except to the extent there has been a waiver, even though there is no burden on the United States.","start":1369.707,"stop":1378.149,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course if you were -- if the military base were involved you would be arguing that the states have absolutely no jurisdiction inside the borders of the land?","start":1378.149,"stop":1389.04,"duration":10.89}]},{"speakerName":"Howard E. Shapiro","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be our contention on any exclusive military enclave.","start":1389.04,"stop":1392.923,"duration":3.88},{"text":"Now there are military bases which are like National Forests in the sense that the federal government hasn’t seeded all civil and military dues -- or has not taken back all civil and military jurisdiction.","start":1392.923,"stop":1405.082,"duration":12.16},{"text":"In those again, we would argue that the tax is like a tax on the Post Exchange or military officer’s club involved in the Mississippi liquor case.","start":1405.082,"stop":1413.382,"duration":8.3},{"text":"We would say it is still falling on a federal instrumentality or a federal function and once we established that then that is the end of any demonstration, any need to demonstrate burden.","start":1413.382,"stop":1423.422,"duration":10.04},{"text":"There is no great burden on the United States if military personnel pay a tax on their liquor.","start":1423.422,"stop":1427.937,"duration":4.51},{"text":"But the court has held that that is nonetheless unconstitutional.","start":1427.937,"stop":1431.316,"duration":3.38},{"text":"The same is true for National Banks or the Red Cross for example.","start":1431.316,"stop":1434.35,"duration":3.03},{"text":"Thank you your Honors.","start":1434.35,"stop":1435.934,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Shapiro.","start":1435.934,"stop":1437.248,"duration":1.31},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":1437.248,"stop":1439.869,"duration":2.62}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Nov  8 - 9, 1976","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"75-1262","citation":"429 US 452 (1977)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/429/452","lowerCourt":"State appellate court","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jan 25, 1977"}